<TITLE> Maldives regularises 16,000 Bangladeshis </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 1 (bdnews24.com)The Maldives government has accorded legal permission to over 16,000 Bangladeshis to stay and work there. Expatriate welfare and overseas employment minister Khandaker Mosharraf Hossain broke the news to the media on Sunday on his return from a four-day trip to the island country. "A total 16,100 Bangladeshis in Maldives had no legal papers. We approached the Maldivian leaders including the president and discussed the matter and then they permitted our people to stay there legally," said the minister. The ministry sources said about 40,000 Bangladeshis now live in the Maldives, which is a small island nation of about three lakh people. The island country faces threat of extinction due to global climate change and especially temperature hike. The Maldives government has demanded shifting its people elsewhere before the impending deluge. On the news published in the Bangladesh media that Maldives will not recruit any more Bangladeshi workers, the minister said, "Bangladesh may be able to send in builders in great numbers if the proposed construction works come off eventually.
